      "detail": "Criminal/state-adjacent adversary model means the derived product portfolio is a target for sophisticated theft or competitive espionage. The derived products contain valuable market intelligence, competitive insights, and analytical capabilities that adversaries would exploit. State-adjacent actors may seek access for economic intelligence or competitive advantage purposes. The adversary model determines the security investment needed to protect the derivation portfolio."
    },
    "Access Control": {
      "value": "RBAC",
      "memo": "Role-based access control governs internal access to derived products and derivation methodology, limiting who can access the processor's leverage-creating assets.",
      "detail": "RBAC access control means internal access to derived products and derivation methodologies is governed by role-based permissions. The controls protect the derivation methodology from internal leakage and ensure derived products are only accessed by authorized teams. RBAC provides basic governance over the assets that create the leverage position. Role-based controls balance operational flexibility with asset protection."
    },
    "Monitoring Scope": {
      "value": "Outputs",
      "memo": "Monitoring covers derivation outputs to ensure product quality and track usage, but input contribution to specific derived products is typically unmonitored.",
      "detail": "Output monitoring means the processor tracks what derived products are created and how they are used commercially. However, the specific contribution of individual inputs to particular derived products is typically unmonitored. This monitoring gap makes it difficult for input suppliers to demonstrate their data's contribution to derivative value. Output-only monitoring supports commercial quality management while maintaining the information asymmetry that enables leverage."
    },
    "Containment": {
      "value": "Policy-only",
      "memo": "Derivation containment is policy-only, with corporate policies governing what derivations are permitted rather than architectural boundaries enforcing derivation limits.",
      "detail": "Policy-only containment means the processor's own policies determine what derivations are created rather than technical enforcement. There are no architectural barriers preventing expansion of derivation scope beyond initial agreements with input suppliers. Policy containment enables the flexibility to find and exploit new derivation opportunities as market opportunities emerge. The policy-only character means derivation scope is limited only by corporate choice, not by technical architecture."
    },
    "Weight Security": {
      "value": "Monitored",
      "memo": "Model weights used for derivation are monitored as proprietary assets because they embody the derivation methodology that creates the leverage position.",
      "detail": "Monitored weight security means the models used for derivation are tracked and protected as proprietary competitive assets. The derivation models represent the methodological advantage that enables the leverage shift from input to derivative value. Monitoring ensures the derivation capability remains exclusive to the processor and is not leaked to competitors. Weight security for derivation models protects the methodology that creates the commercial leverage."
    },
    "Capability Limitation": {
      "value": "None",
      "memo": "No capability limitation constrains derivation because the processor faces no architectural restriction on what transformations can be applied to licensed input data.",
      "detail": "No capability limitation means the processor can apply any derivation technique to licensed inputs without technical restriction. The absence of limitation enables the processor to continuously discover new derivation value from existing data. Users and suppliers have no mechanism to limit what derivations are created from their contributed data. No capability limitation is the technical condition that enables the leverage shift through unconstrained derivation."
    },
    "Use Class": {
      "value": "Civilian",
      "memo": "Derivative lever operates in civilian commercial use class where the economic value shift is driven by commercial data markets and competitive dynamics.",
      "detail": "Civilian use class means the leverage shift occurs within normal commercial data markets and competitive business dynamics. The economic analysis is about commercial power, not about military or national security implications. Civilian context determines the regulatory framework and the competitive dynamics that shape the leverage position. Civilian use class keeps the stance focused on commercial data economics."
    },
    "Harm Channel": {
      "value": "Information",
      "memo": "Derivative lever creates information-channel effects where value extraction through derivation shifts economic power from data suppliers to data processors.",
      "detail": "Information harm channel means the primary economic effect flows through information asymmetry and data market power dynamics. The harm to input suppliers is economic, not physical, operating through value extraction that erodes their commercial position. Information-channel effects include loss of bargaining power, commoditization of inputs, and dependency on the processor's derived products. The information channel is where the leverage shift manifests as commercial power redistribution."
    },
    "Proliferation": {
      "value": "Licensed diffusion",
      "memo": "Derived products proliferate through licensed commercial distribution to customers, with the processor controlling the diffusion rate and terms of derived data access.",
      "detail": "Licensed diffusion means derived products spread to customers through commercial licensing rather than open or uncontrolled distribution. The processor controls the rate, terms, and scope of derived product access as a commercial distribution decision. Licensed diffusion enables the processor to monetize derivatives while maintaining control over access and pricing. The distribution model determines how widely the derived-data leverage extends across the market."
    },
    "Coalition Structure": {
      "value": "Single firm",
      "memo": "Derivative lever is typically a single-firm strategy where one processor captures derivation value from multiple input suppliers without sharing with competitors.",
      "detail": "Single firm coalition means one processor captures derivation value exclusively, creating an asymmetric relationship with input suppliers. The single-firm structure enables the processor to aggregate inputs from multiple suppliers without any individual supplier seeing the cross-source value. Single-firm derivation prevents competitive erosion of the leverage position through rival derivation offerings. The single-firm character concentrates the leverage and the value capture in the processing entity."
    },
    "Nonproliferation Regime": {
      "value": "None",
      "memo": "No nonproliferation regime governs derived-data markets, leaving the value shift from input suppliers to processors entirely unregulated by specific frameworks.",
      "detail": "No nonproliferation regime means there are no specific controls on the creation, distribution, or concentration of derived-data market power. The regulatory vacuum enables unrestricted derivation and commercialisation of products created from licensed inputs. The absence of specific regulation means the leverage shift is constrained only by general competition law and contract. No regime is the regulatory condition that enables derived-data leverage to develop unchecked."
    },
    "Data Value Dynamics": {
      "value": "Rivalrous",
      "memo": "Derived data exhibits rivalrous value dynamics because derived products create exclusive competitive advantage that diminishes when competitors access equivalent products.",
      "detail": "Rivalrous value means derived products lose competitive value when competitors obtain equivalent analytical capabilities. This is the central paradox of derivation: non-rivalrous inputs are transformed into rivalrous outputs through computational processing. The rivalrous character of derived data is what creates the leverage shift because exclusive access to derivatives has competitive value. Rivalrous dynamics drive the commercial urgency to control derivation and derived product distribution."
    },
    "Input Price": {
      "value": "Fixed",
      "memo": "Input suppliers receive fixed pricing that does not reflect the derivative value their data enables, creating the price gap that represents the leverage shift.",
      "detail": "Fixed input pricing means suppliers are paid a predetermined amount regardless of what derivative value their data generates. The fixed price was typically negotiated before the derivative market existed or before the supplier understood derivative potential. The gap between fixed input cost and variable derivative revenue is the economic measure of the leverage shift. Fixed pricing that fails to capture derivative value is the economic mechanism through which leverage transfers to the processor."
    },
    "Output Allocation": {
      "value": "Claimed derivatives",
      "memo": "The processor claims all derivative outputs as proprietary products, allocating zero derivative ownership to the input suppliers whose data enabled their creation.",
      "detail": "Claimed derivatives means the processor asserts full ownership of all products derived from licensed inputs. Input suppliers receive no share of derivative value regardless of how essential their data was to the derivation. The claimed-derivatives allocation is the contractual expression of the leverage shift from supplier to processor. Claimed derivative ownership without supplier participation is the value allocation mechanism of the leverage pattern."
    },
    "Derived Value Capture": {
      "value": "Processor captures",
      "memo": "The processor captures all derived value, creating the core leverage dynamic where downstream derivatives become more valuable than the upstream inputs that produced them.",
